    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does elderberry with zinc and vitamin C actually boost immunity?</summary>
      <p>Each component has independent clinical evidence. Elderberry reduced cold duration by 2 days (2019 meta-analysis). Zinc reduced cold duration by 33% (2017 Cochrane review). Vitamin C reduces cold duration by 8% prophylactically. The combination targets three distinct immune pathways — antiviral, T-cell activation, and innate immune support.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much elderberry should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>For preventive support: 300-600mg standardized extract daily. During illness: up to 1,200mg daily divided into 3-4 doses. Look for products standardized to anthocyanin content, the primary bioactive class for immune modulation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take elderberry gummies every day?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Studies show daily elderberry for 10-16 weeks is safe with no adverse effects. It reduced incidence and severity of upper respiratory infections in frequent travelers. 300-600mg daily is appropriate for maintenance; increase temporarily during illness.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What form of zinc is best for immune support?</summary>
      <p>Zinc bisglycinate and zinc picolinate offer highest bioavailability. Zinc citrate is also well-absorbed and common in gummies. Avoid zinc oxide (lowest absorption). Maintain 8-11mg daily for maintenance; up to 25-40mg short-term during illness. Do not exceed 40mg daily long-term to avoid copper depletion.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is elderberry safe for people with autoimmune conditions?</summary>
      <p>The "cytokine storm" concern has been largely debunked — elderberry's cytokine response is orders of magnitude below pathological levels. However, since elderberry stimulates immune activity, consult your rheumatologist if you have lupus, RA, or MS before supplementing.</p>
    </details>

